Right-wing populists triumph in Austria, collectively 29 percent
The significant weakening of the two parties in the previous grand coalition and the significant strengthening of the right-wing populist parties have led to early parliamentary elections in Austria on Sunday, according to the first preliminary results.
The Austrian People's Party (ÖVP) has suffered particularly heavy losses, with the position of current chairman Wilhelm Molterer seriously shaken.
In contrast, the electoral leader of the Union for the Future of Austria (BZÖ), the Korutansk hechtman Jörg Haider, is preparing a triumphant return to national politics.
According to preliminary results, the Social Democratic Party (SPÖ) remains the strongest party in the country with 29.8 percent of the vote, but it is losing 5.5 percent of the vote compared to the last elections in 2006.
Even worse was the case with the ÖVP, which lost almost nine percent of the vote with 25.6 percent.
It is the worst result of both of these big parties in the post-war history of Austria and especially for the people who called early elections, a literally disastrous result.
In early July, when the ÖVP withdrew from the coalition, the People's Party had a considerable lead over the SPÖ in preferences.
But voters apparently punished them for letting the government fall.
Early reactions to the results have been speculative about the possible resignation of party chairman and former vice-chancellor Wilhelm Molter.
Observers say that could happen as early as Monday at an extraordinary party leadership meeting.
Such a development would probably facilitate the path to the increasingly likely exit from the election result, namely the renewal of the SPÖ-ÖVP grand coalition.
However, given the strengthening of the two right-wing populist parties - the Free Party (FPÖ) which had obtained a preliminary 18 percent and the BZÖ 11 percent of the vote - the Social Democrats also expressed concern about a repeat of 1999, when the People's Party agreed with the populists (the FPÖ was still united, but split from the BZÖ in 2005) to form a joint government, which even triggered sanctions from the European Union.
This is clearly the development Haider is betting on, who has already declared that he is ready to cooperate with any party and envisages a return to Vienna in national politics.
The Greens also entered the parliament, but lost slightly and fell from third to fifth place among Austrian political parties.
None of the other parties apparently crossed the four percent threshold and did not get into parliament.
