Turkey's diplomatic horizons are widening
Long before Turkey began its bid for European Union membership, the European powers were eager to penetrate deep into Turkey's hinterland.
On the eastern shore of the Bosporus, perhaps only twenty steps in Asia, stands one of the finest monuments of this failed imperial ambition.
Hydarpasha Railway Station was designed by two German architects Otto Ritter and Helmut Conu in a Neo-Renaissance style.
Well, that's what the tour guides will tell you.
The building sits circular at the end of the platforms with towers on each corner of the facade, for an indistinguishable view from some provincial German town hall.
The stone is dirty.
The whole building is falling apart.
But once you get inside the gated register, you can't doubt the size of the establishment whose westernmost gateway was the station.
The station was opened in August 1908 by the German consortium Anatolian-Baghdad Corporation.
Germany, which had entered the game of empire late, intended to realize its ambition to control the Middle East with this railway, which would lead to Damascus, Baghdad and on to what is now Saudi Arabia.
But German imperial ambitions collapsed during World War I.
Their tracks were attacked by Lawrence of Arabia and his irregular troops.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories created by the frozen borders of the Cold War is gone.
British and colonial troops were advancing from Egypt, pushing the Turks and their German allies out of Palestine and Syria.
And there's bad news for Hydarpasha station as well.
In 1917, an explosion of a munitions train destroyed its elaborate roof.
Turkish sources say it was sabotage.
Since then, it has been gradually being torn down and history has circled it.
Today, however, this gateway to Anatolia and further east serves - at least symbolically - to highlight the expanding horizons of Turkish diplomacy.
The ruling Justice and Development Party (AKP) has created a completely new foreign policy for the country.
The relative isolation from the surrounding territories created by the frozen borders of the Cold War is gone.
Now a new policy is being implemented - Turkey is getting involved.
It is remarkable that the Turkish government has good relations with Israel and Syria, with the Palestinian factions Hamas and Fatah, with Iraq and Iran, and of course with the European Union and the United States.
To review the parameters of this new policy, I boarded a night train to the Turkish capital, Ankara, where I was to meet with one of the leading AKP foreign policy experts, Turkish MP Suat Kiniklioglu.
The next morning - about ten and a half hours later - after a winding ride along the tracks that recalled the old-world rhythms of the famous documentary Night Post, I arrived in a Turkish metropolis, designed as a new city for a secular state that wants to turn its back on its Ottoman past.
However, the AKP with its well-known Islamist roots represents a paradigm shift of the Turkish consensus.
She has aroused suspicion in the West, especially in Washington.
The taxi took me to the AKP headquarters, a state-of-the-art stone and metal building, deliberately built on a developing suburb, surrounded by half-timbered department stores and power stores, where middle managers in business suits - men and women - meet to make early morning trades.
Suat Kiniklioglu could easily be a centre-right politician from almost any other European political party.
Sako, tie, I'm sure he had a Blackberry.
"The aim of the party's foreign policy is to reintegrate Turkey into its immediate surroundings.
The Cold War was an anomaly", he told me.
Turkey was cut off from its territory.
Today, you have to look east and west at the same time.
It wasn't a choice.
It must have done both.
"But surely there will come a time", I asked, "when Turkey may have to make a decision?"
"Turkey", he said, "did not wish that such a decision had to be made".
He then pointed out what almost everyone I spoke to here had said almost by heart: Turkey's relations not only with the Middle East, but also with the Caucasus and the Black Sea region are as beneficial to Europe and the United States as they are to Turkey.
With Turkey on board, it seems that Europe as a whole can, metaphorically speaking, go east on these rails to Asia and the Middle East.
Back at Hydarpasha Station, after another mostly sleepless night, I thought of those two German gentlemen, Herr Ritter and Herr Cona, who watched this building being built a hundred years ago.
How surprised they would be to find out that European ambitions in the Middle East may now be, in substantial part, in Turkish hands.
And as I waited at the port for the ferry back across the Bosporus, I remembered that in those days Turkey was called "the sick man of Europe".
So it seems that at least at the time, there was little doubt as to which continent should claim this fascinating land.
