The Bee Car prevents rainfall
To advance the development of accident protection technologies, Nissan has this time been inspired by nature, specifically bees.
This Japanese company has developed a robot that mimics the flight of bees, thus preventing collisions.
One of them is the Bio-mimetic Car Robot Drive, or BR23C, which is the first step in collision-prevention technology.
Engineers at the Nissan Motor Co.'s Center for Technical Advancement have developed the robot in collaboration with the Center for Scientific and Technological Advancement Research at the prestigious University of Tokyo in Japan.
According to Kazuhiro Doie, general manager of public relations for technology, research and development of the brand, the BR23C is presented as an extension of the four zones of the Nissan safety shield.
The robot's mission is to enhance the collision prevention capability of the vehicles of this brand.
During flight, each bee creates its own personal oval-shaped space, which is very similar to a Nissan safety shield.
Most important, though, are the compound eyes of bees, which can see in all directions at an angle greater than 300 degrees, allowing the bees to fly in their personal space without stopping.
In creating this visual feature, the engineers designed what they called a laser range finder.
It shall record obstacles up to a distance of 2 metres within a 180° radius of the BR23C, calculate the distance of the object and send a signal to the on-board microprocessor which shall immediately convert it into a collision warning.
"When an obstacle is detected, the robot mimics the movements of the bee and immediately changes direction by turning the wheels to the right or even a greater angle to prevent a collision.
The biggest difference from any existing system is the fact that all the bending maneuvers are completely instinctive.
If it were not, the robot would not be able to react quickly enough to avoid obstacles", explains Toshiyuki Andoh, director of the Mobile Laboratory and chief engineer of the project.
Unlike bees, the robot cannot move up and down or diagonally, its movement is limited to two dimensions and the direction made possible by the rotation of its wheels, but not to an infinite number of directions and possibilities as in bees.
So Nissan used the rotation function to prevent the robot from crashing, in addition to accelerating and slowing down.
"The device only needs to process information every few seconds and behave according to that data.
It requires no retention of information or logical intuition from previous maneuvers, allowing it to operate without interruption with only two dozen kB of memory.
You may be surprised, but we don't talk about gigabytes or mega-gigs in memory".
This is the first step in the development of new technologies for immediate collision prevention, technologies that Nissan predicts will be used in production cars within a decade.
The robot uses lithium polymer batteries, which are lighter and last longer than lithium-ion batteries.
Another possible future use of this technology could be to incorporate a unit into a GPS satellite navigation system, which would guide the driver to his destination while avoiding obstacles on the road.
