It goes without saying that Rafael Correa has received congratulations from Chavez and Morales, but also from his Chilean counterpart, Michelle Bachelet.
The vote, which was conducted in a calm manner, according to the Organization of American States (OAS) observation mission, was on a 444-point text building the "new socialism" promoted by the president.
The draft constitution enshrines state power over the economy by reserving to it the "development planning" of a country that lives primarily on oil extraction by foreign companies and foreign exchange sent by its emigrants.
The proposal, which was backed by Corre, who was elected in 2006, also extends the powers of the head of state, who will be able to serve two consecutive four-year terms and will be able to dissolve the parliament.
