Egyptian commandos have attacked the kidnappers of 11 tourists and their eight-member escort, who were captured 10 days ago.
They're in Cairo.
Eleven European tourists and their eight Egyptian guides, who had been held captive in the desert for ten days, were safely transported to the Egyptian capital on Monday.
They were liberated by the Egyptian commandos in Chad during the morning.
The hostages arrived at about 15:30, apparently in good shape, aboard a special aircraft to the al-Maza military base, adjacent to Cairo International Airport.
They were immediately transported, without the possibility of commenting to the press, by helicopter to a hospital in Maadi, a residential suburb of Cairo, for medical examination.
"They are in perfect health" and "no ransom has been paid to the kidnappers", said Egyptian Tourism Minister Zoheir Garrana at the airport runway.
Since their capture on September 19th during an all-wheel drive safari at the foot of Mount Uanat, on the borders of Egypt, Sudan and Libya, a group of hostages have been dragged from one hiding place to another by 35 unknown kidnappers.
The group includes 11 tourists - five Italians, five Germans and one Romanian - as well as eight Egyptians: two guides, four drivers, one border guard, the director of the Aegyptous agency, the safari organiser.
A senior Egyptian security official indicated that 30 members of the special forces, who had approached the scene in two helicopters, had set off for the battlefield during the night just before dawn.
"There was a shootout, half the kidnappers were killed and the rest fled", said the source, who wished to remain anonymous.
He pointed out that a total of 150 members of the Egyptian special forces unit "Blitz" were sent to Sudan, where they received support from German and Italian commandos.
From Belgrade, where he is currently, the Italian Foreign Minister Franco Frattini spoke of the role played by secret agents and elements of the Italian special forces.
"We have to acknowledge that we have achieved this result because of the professionalism and efficiency of our intelligence people, our special forces", he said, without further specification.
He also denied that the ransom had been paid.
Earlier in the evening, the Sudanese military said it had intercepted the four-wheel-drive vehicle carrying the hijackers on patrol, killing six, including the Chadian commander, and arresting two.
The army claimed that they were connected to the Darfur rebel group, the Sudan Liberation Army-Unity (SLA-U), which the movement immediately denied.
