Benelux Governments the state-owned part of Fortis Bank
The Benelux countries will help the Belgian-Dutch bank Fortis, which was the first in Europe to be in difficulty due to the widening impact of the crisis on the US mortgage market, by partially nationalising it: the three countries will support the money and insurance institution, which also has a capital stake in Hungary, with EUR 11.2 billion.
The Belgian, Luxembourg and Dutch governments agreed at the highest level this weekend, with the President of the European Central Bank and the European Commissioner for Competition.
Fortis is the first euro area bank to be hit by a major crisis in the context of the crisis on international financial markets, which has been raging for more than a year, and the decisions taken in this regard could in some respects be regarded as precedents.
Under the decision, which was adopted on Sunday night, all three countries will buy back almost half (49%) of the bank's assets there.
The Bank will sell with absolute certainty part of its capital holdings, mainly insurance activities, which it purchased from the Dutch bank ABN Amro last year.
Fortis' stock began to fall sharply last week, and by the second half of the week, the institution was already showing serious signs of a crisis.
But analysts agree that with 85,000 employees, the bank is too big to let it go bankrupt.
The company's stock fell 12 percent on Friday alone, to a 14-year low.
The stock has fallen by more than two-thirds since January.
In view of the current share prices, the total market capitalisation of the group is around EUR 14 billion, but according to the company's management this is unrealistic.
The management blames the fall in Fortis' shares on the uncertainty in the overseas market related to the adoption of the US $700 billion package.
The stock's already up slightly on Monday.
On Friday, the new CEO, Filip Dierckx, was appointed to the bank.
The Mint was also looking for private buyers, but no one has come forward with a more serious offer.
The Belgian Government has already announced that investors do not have to worry about losing their money.
There has been no panic among the bank's clients and the branches have not been attacked.
In Hungary, Fortis has a separate branch and has also acquired several leasing companies.
The fox in the henhouse
Life and health insurance companies in America often reject the possibility of contracting insurance with the applicant based on people's drug purchasing records.
Data protection experts fear that the data market will become uncontrollable.
'There is a data protection programme which binds the use of prescription data in all cases to the consent of the person concerned.
It has to be in the hands of an independent person, or we're leaving the chicken coop to the fox", quotes the Washington Post Richard Dicke, author of a program designed to monitor prescription drugs.
Insurance companies make the premiums and the amounts paid in the event of insured events dependent on the health status of the persons concerned and, if the risk is assessed as too great, do not take out insurance with them.
In the past, they sent people for medical examinations and only signed contracts after they knew the results.
A decade ago, Dick devised a much cheaper method: a pharmacy customer's ID number would easily tell the pharmacist what medication he or she had purchased in the past year and a half, from which the program would infer the patient's medical condition.
For example, if he regularly buys large amounts of cholesterol-lowering medication, it indicates that he has practically uncontrollably high blood lipids, which immediately puts him in the higher-risk category.
Several versions of the programme are in circulation, some of which also determine the risk factor, so that there is almost no work left to do at the insurance company except for the paperwork, although there are minor difficulties.
The disadvantages are that some medicines can be used for several purposes, some compounds are useful for migraines or hot flashes, but they are also effective against depression.
They represent a significant risk-increasing factor from the point of view of commercial insurers, whereas the first mentioned difficulties do not.
Special companies have been set up to request and process the data, and they ask the patient for permission before they can obtain the necessary information from the pharmacies.
They are now being forced to do so by the authorities, even though they have not been punished for their negligence.
Some companies have recently been processing the results of laboratory tests and combining them with the data on the medicines they use, thus providing an even more accurate picture of the health of patients.
Data is increasingly being accessed by more companies, and controlling its use will be increasingly difficult.
There is a special law on the protection of health data, but it is only applicable to healthcare providers and insurance companies.
A bill that would give the government the power to control companies that specialize in providing data is before Congress.
Richard Dick recognises that this is not enough: he has therefore developed his programme so that the transmission of data is subject to the explicit consent of the person concerned.
Another thing is that he can hardly refuse the authorization in question, otherwise the insurance companies will not contract with him.
So chickens are somewhat dependent on the goodwill fox.
