The EU and India to double trade
As the European Union and India are each other's leading trading partners, this topic, alongside other, mostly global issues, also topped the agenda of the ninth summit.
The French-Indian summit will also be held today, with a focus on cooperation in the field of atomic energy.
The European Union recognises that India is an emerging democratic power which should be given a greater say in international affairs, but the Member States have so far failed to find a common denominator on the issue of supporting New Delhi's permanent membership of the UN Security Council.
The question was not even discussed further at yesterday's ninth summit in Marseille.
French President Nicolas Sarkozy, the EU's current President, and European Commission President José Manuel Barroso and the High Representative for Foreign Affairs Javier Solana welcomed Indian Prime Minister Manmohan Singh, with whom they also agreed to double trade turnover to more than €100 billion in five years.
Given that trade in goods increased from 25 billion to 55 billion between 2000 and 2007, this is not an overly ambitious target.
