The plane of Steve Fossett, the millionaire who disappeared a year ago, has been found.
The remains of the plane of Steve Fossett, a millionaire who disappeared on September 3, 2007, were found while flying over the Nevada desert.
The wreckage was discovered on a plateau at an elevation of 3,000 feet in the Mammoth Lakes region of Sierra Nevada, on the border between California and Nevada.
However, there were no human remains inside the plane.
Madera County Sheriff John Anderson dispelled any remaining suspicions: "The plane was found, we sent a team there, and we now know for sure that it's exactly the same plane that Steve Fossett was flying on the day he disappeared", he told a news conference.
So the sheriff made it clear that no human remains were found on the plane or in the surrounding area.
The 63-year-old millionaire has been considered dead since February.
The US Transportation Safety Bureau (TSB) announced that several hours after the wreckage was identified, an investigative team was dispatched to finally identify the plane: it was, precisely, a Bellanca 8kcab, missing since 3 September 2007, when Fossett took off from Yerington, Nevada for a three-hour flight.
Yesterday, still in California, near the Nevada border, some of Fossett's personal effects were found by a couple near their home in Mammoth Lakes.
It's two documents in Fossett's name, both issued by the Illinois Federal Aviation Administration, cash and a jacket.
The search for Fossett was stopped a month after he disappeared.
The billionaire earned a place in history thanks to a long collection of firsts.
In 2002, on his sixth attempt, he became the first man to complete a round-the-world flight in a hot air balloon: two weeks of solo flight.
Three years later, he flew around the world without landing.
Among his many records is the flight to an altitude of 15,445 meters over the Andes, even though he was a co-pilot.
